<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCIENCE CALENDAR: OBSERVATORY TRACES LAST YEAR OF COMET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NONA YATES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 When Comet Shoemaker-Levy crashed into Jupiter in July, it was one of the 
most-watched astronomical events in modern times. The Griffith Observatory's 
new multimedia planetarium program examines the comet from discovery to its 
fiery demise.  
</P>
<P>
 "Comet Crash" examines Comet Shoemaker-Levy from its discovery at Palomar 
Observatory in 1993 to its spectacular collision with the giant planet, 
observed by almost every major telescope in the world. 
</P>
<P>
 The program also evaluates the risk of such an event to Earth and assesses 
what might be done to avert such a catastrophe. It will run through Dec. 11. 
(213) 664-1191. 
</P>
<P>
 SEISMOLOGY 
</P>
<P>
 * The Los Angeles Community Reuse Organization will host a workshop on the 
Northridge earthquake at the Department of Energy Technology Engineering Center 
near Chatsworth at 9:30 a.m. Saturday. (818) 586-6424. 
</P>
<P>
 SCIENCE FOR FAMILIES 
</P>
<P>
 * Children 8 and older with an adult can take a behind-the-scenes tour of the 
collection of whale, dolphin, walrus, seal and sea otter skeletons at the 
Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County's Marine Mammal Research Facility 
in Vernon on Saturday at 1 p.m. Advance registration required. (213) 744-3534. 
</P>
<P>
 SCIENCE POLICY 
</P>
<P>
 * "Redefining Environmentalism: Questions of Gender, Race and Class" will be 
discussed by Robert Gottlieb, of the UCLA Department of Urban Planning, at the 
Caltech Seminar on Science, Ethics and Public Policy at 4 p.m. Thursday in the 
Judy Library. (818) 395-4652. 
</P>
<P>
 * Deborah Blum, Pulitzer Prize-winning author of "The Monkey Wars," will 
discuss the controversy of using primates in research at 7 p.m. Thursday at the 
George C. Page Museum (213) 744-3534, and at 2 p.m. Sunday at Caltech's Baxter 
Lecture Hall (818) 794-3119. 
</P>
<P>
 * Princeton professor Charles F. Westoff will discuss "Population Prospects 
and Policies for the 21st Century" at noon Monday at the Pomona College Blue 
Room, Frank Dining Hall. (909) 621-3026. 
</P>
<P>
 METEOROLOGY 
</P>
<P>
 * Robert Farber, senior research scientist for Southern California Edison, 
will discuss "Changing Trends in Visibility in the Los Angeles Basin and the 
Colorado Plateau," at the American Meteorological Society at 8 p.m. Wednesday 
at the Edison building in Rosemead. Call (213) 343-2222. 
</P>
<P>
 * The colony of water birds, including some endangered species, at the Bolsa 
Chica Ecological Reserve will be the topic at the Pasadena Audubon Society 
meeting at 7:30 p.m. Wednesday at the Los Angeles County Arboretum. (818) 
798-5522. NONA YATES 
