<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: THOUSAND OAKS; PASSENGER INJURED IN DUNE BUGGY 
ACCIDENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG RIPPEE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Newbury Park man broke his leg and two other men escaped serious injury 
after their dune buggy overturned on a hillside while they were riding on dirt 
trails at night in west Thousand Oaks, sheriff's deputies said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 Ryan Spaeth, 20, was injured after the 1962 Volkswagen rolled over his leg 
about 10 p.m. Sunday, just moments after he tried to leap free from the 
vehicle, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 Spaeth, whose right leg was broken, was reported in satisfactory 
conditionMonday night at Los Robles Regional Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
 The driver of the off-road vehicle, Brett Compositor, 20, of Westlake, was 
driving in the Hill Canyon area off Rancho Conejo Boulevard when the Volkswagen 
lost power and began to roll backward, deputies said. 
</P>
<P>
 As the buggy began to flip, Spaeth unfastened his seat belt and jumped while 
Compositor and another passenger, 20-year-old Brian Meany of Newbury Park, 
remained in the car, deputies said. 
</P>
<P>
 They said neither Compositor nor Meany, who were wearing their seat belts, 
were injured. 
</P>
<P>
 The accident remained under investigation, deputies said. GREG RIPPEE 
</P>
