<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMPANY TOWN; SAVOY, FOX RESTRUCTURE VENTURE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In an effort to speed government clearance and deflate objections to its 
proposed purchase of TV stations, SF Broadcasting has changed its corporate 
structure. But NBC said it will continue to challenge the deals. 
</P>
<P>
 SF Broadcasting, owned by Savoy Pictures Entertainment Inc. and News Corp.'s 
Fox Television Stations Inc., had formed limited liability companies to buy TV 
stations in Green Bay, Wis., and three other cities. It planned to make them 
affiliates of the Fox TV network. 
</P>
<P>
 Savoy executives had all of the voting power under the original structure; Fox 
and Savoy had no votes. 
</P>
<P>
 NBC recently complained that the arrangement appeared to be aimed at enabling 
Fox to circumvent Federal Communications Commission limits on how many stations 
one company can own. The Green Bay station is its affiliate. 
</P>
<P>
 FCC rules set the limit at 12. Fox already owns nine stations. SF Broadcasting 
said its stations would not be counted against the Fox total. 
</P>
<P>
 In a filing with the FCC, SF Broadcasting said Friday that it has converted 
the company formed to buy WLUK in Green Bay into a corporation in which Savoy 
Pictures would have 75% of the equity and all of the voting shares. Fox would 
own 25% of the equity and no voting shares. The Savoy executives would not be 
shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
 Thomas Herwitz, president and chief executive of SF Broadcasting, said the new 
structure has been used in hundreds of station buyouts and should eliminate 
objections to the ownership arrangement. The stations would not count against 
Fox's station limit because Fox has no voting control over them, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 He said similar changes will be made in the applications SF Broadcasting filed 
to buy stations in Honolulu, New Orleans and Mobile, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
 NBC still has objections, said its general counsel, Richard Cotton. 
</P>
<P>
 He said NBC will ask the FCC to examine how much control Fox has over their 
hiring and network affiliation and over the stations' financial matters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
