<HEADLINE>
<P>
ANGOLAN GOVERNMENT, REBELS REACH ACCORD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Negotiators for the Angolan government and rebels agreed to a peace treaty 
Monday to end their 19-year civil war, pledging a cease-fire, disarmament and 
creation of a new army. 
</P>
<P>
 Alioune Blondin Beye, the U.N. special representative who mediated the 
negotiations, said the 10-point agreement seeks not just to silence the guns 
but to heal the divisions that have led to the deaths of more than half a 
million Angolans. 
</P>
