<HEADLINE>
<P>
CULTURE; EGYPT'S SLEEPING BEAUTY REVIVED AFTER 3,200 YEARS; RESTORING THE TOMB 
OF QUEEN NEFERTARI RAISES PROFOUND ISSUES OF ART AND HISTORY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WILLIAM D. MONTALBANO, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Then, she was cherished across Egypt for her beauty and her brains. Now, the 
queen known to history as Nefertari is reaching across more than 3,000 years to 
raise some provocative questions about the future. 
</P>
<P>
 What in the world among the myriad relics of yesterday is worth conserving for 
coming generations? Save that building? Save this feather? And, since it's 
impossible to save everything, what should time and old age be allowed to have 
their way with? 
</P>
<P>
 The ancient queen is a jewel, worth keeping, because she illustrates these 
questions and their challenges. 
</P>
<P>
 Nefertari, literally "the most beautiful," was the first wife and favorite 
consort of mighty Ramses II, who reigned 1290-1224 BC. She lived about 45 
years, circa 1300-1255 BC. He prized her companionship and counsel, loaded her 
with titles such as "mother and wife of god in life," and built her a 
spectacular tomb (before marrying their eldest daughter). 
</P>
<P>
 To speed his beloved's journey to eternity, Ramses stocked the tomb with 
jewels, amulets and funerary statuettes of black-painted sycamore; they were 
supposed to spring to life to serve Nefertari in the afterlife. Tomb stockers 
also thoughtfully left a queenly pair of corded sandals -- and the era's best 
wall paintings. 
</P>
<P>
 Forgotten centuries ago, grave robbers looted the queen's burial chamber, her 
treasures and the mummy itself. But in 1904, Nefertari's resting place in the 
Valley of the Queens near Luxor was discovered for science by an Italian 
diplomat and a more-than-amateur archeologist named Ernesto Schiaparelli. 
</P>
<P>
 Now, after new scholarship and six years of painstaking restoration, Nefertari 
and her burial chamber are subjects of a pioneer exhibition that opened here 
this month, blending artifacts with the theme of conservation and the high-tech 
wonderland of virtual reality. 
</P>
<P>
 The Louvre, the British Museum and the Egyptian Museum in Schiaparelli's 
native Turin have all contributed to a show whose artifacts range from an 
exquisite bezeled ring inscribed with the names of Ramses and Nefertari to a 
brooding, five-ton Colossus of Ramses. 
</P>
<P>
 In death, Nefertari, who lived one century and one dynasty later than the 
equally famous Nefertiti, reveals volumes about her life and times. The exhibit 
documents the checker-like solitaire game she fancied. It showcases her 
timeless beauty and the reverence she inspired three millennia ago as "the lady 
of fascination," "the sweetness of love," "the divine one." 
</P>
<P>
 The paintings are underscored with hieroglyphics. One depicts Nefertari's 
ritual acceptance by the gods of the afterlife, with one of them greeting her: 
"When you came to me, I gave you a place in the holy ground. May you appear in 
the sky like your father, Ra."  
</P>
<P>
 There is a more down-to-earth message in the exhibition, though. "This is the 
first time an exhibition has brought conservation into the life of an 
exhibition. We want to raise people's consciousness about conservation as an 
extension of art," said Mahasti Afshar, who assembled the show for the Getty 
Conservation Institute.  
</P>
<P>
 The Malibu-based Getty paid several million dollars for the restorations in 
Egypt by Italian experts as part of a worldwide program to find new ways of 
diagnosis and treatment that improve art conservation. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are really talking about conservation of the future, not the past," said 
Miguel Angel Corzo, director of the Getty institute. "With Nefertari, we are 
attracting people with the magic and mystery of Egypt and showing them the 
results of a complex conservation project. We are selling the message of the 
importance of conservation -- and conservation appropriate to the specific 
project." 
</P>
<P>
 The Nefertari burial chamber, as a case in point, is perhaps the most 
important of all the royal tombs in Egypt, Corzo said. Its wall paintings, rich 
in color and symbolism, tell the ancient Egyptian story of the passage of a 
soul to eternity. 
</P>
<P>
 Schiaparelli was appalled at the ravages of time and vandals on the art when 
he discovered the tomb. He introduced turn- of-the-century science to his 
studies, importing a photographer and a surveyor in a quest for accuracy. 
Merely opening the tomb upset a delicate atmospheric balance. 
</P>
<P>
 Corzo said that in a large Egyptian tomb nowadays, the typical daily presence 
of 3,500 visitors adds 11 gallons of water to the air. Over time, the increased 
humidity leaches salt from the limestone and damages painted plaster walls. 
</P>
<P>
 Photographic studies of Nefertari's tomb over the decades since Schiaparelli's 
photographer took the first pictures show dramatic and accelerating 
deterioration of the art. Italian specialists, who are among the world's top 
restorers, did an emergency intervention to stop flaking, cracking and falling 
plaster, and then undertook systematic conservation of the tomb. 
</P>
<P>
 The result is a 3,000-year-old work of art that is once again strikingly bold 
and fresh-looking. But the restorers added not a drop of paint. 
</P>
<P>
 "Conservation must respect the historical integrity of a piece without adding 
anything. It must be a minimalist intervention that does nothing irreversible," 
said Afshar, the man who assembled the show. 
</P>
<P>
 Nefertari's legacy might have been lost entirely without restoration. But in 
presenting the results of its rescue, the exhibit also underlines a modern 
dilemma: can-do technology versus tight resources. 
</P>
<P>
 "In the past, the works of art that were saved were those that survived 
misadventures like decay, looting and earthquakes. Today, we have the 
possibility of saving everything," Corzo said. "Books, feathers, photographs, 
buildings, leather, silk. Techniques are available for all of them -- but never 
the resources." 
</P>
<P>
 In the Czech Republic, Corzo noted, there are 40,000 architectural monuments. 
Which among them to save? If you had a collection of 45,000 old photographs, 
would you save all of them? Just the best? 
</P>
<P>
 "We are poised to decide how we want future generations to look at the past," 
Corzo said. 
</P>
<P>
 Decisions are not easy. At a major archeological site, there may be as many 
conflicting interests as there are parties with a stake: archeologists, 
scholars, conservators, government ministries of tourism and finance, people 
living around the site and those making money from it. 
</P>
<P>
 There are trade-offs: Nefertari's tomb, long beloved of visitors, is now 
safely restored. But it is also closed to visitors who once streamed through in 
awe. Egyptian authorities are conferring with atmospheric monitoring machines 
to decide how many people could be allowed in without triggering run-amok 
deterioration. 
</P>
<P>
 There are uncertainties: Nefertari's tomb ranks high on any list of monuments 
worth saving. But if Muslim fundamentalism were to force the interest of some 
future Egyptian government away from cultural preservation, the money spent on 
Nefertari might, in retrospect, have been better spent on some other worthy 
rescue. 
</P>
<P>
 There are challenges: To give people an idea of the scope and majesty of the 
tomb, Schiaparelli's team made a breathtaking one-tenth scale model that is 
among the current show's exhibits. The model was, effectively, virtual reality, 
circa 1910. Its modern counterpart at the show here is a computer-driven tour 
of the tomb -- virtual reality, circa 2000. 
</P>
<P>
 In the cutting-edge exhibition fashioned by ENEL, Italy's power and light 
company, visitors stroll about the tomb with the aid of a joystick. Walk in, 
turn corners, raise and lower your gaze, focus on individual paintings and 
symbols. It is an eerie, simultaneous encounter with the Egyptian otherworld 
and the computer next-world. 
</P>
<P>
 Indeed, one of Nefertari's come-from-the-past lessons may be that while it is 
not possible to conserve everything, technology may make it possible for 
curious souls in the next century to realistically savor shards of yesterday 
through marvels of electronic conservation now glimmering on tomorrow's 
horizon. 
</P>
<P>
 "Nefertari, Light of Egypt" is at the Palazzo Ruspoli, Via del Corso 118, 
until Feb. 19, 1995. The exhibit is open daily from 10 a.m. to 8:30 p.m. and 
until 10 p.m. on Saturdays. Tickets are about $6.75.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA101894-0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 089774 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
October 18, 1994, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
