<HEADLINE>
<P>
DUCKS' CARNBACK WILL PROBABLY PLAY IN SWEDEN DURING LOCKOUT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBYN NORWOOD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Mighty Duck forward Patrik Carnback will play for Frolunda, his former Swedish 
professional team, "unless something dramatic happens (in the NHL lockout 
situation)," his agent said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 Neil Abbott, Carnback's Boston-based agent, hoped to have the Ducks assign 
Carnback to Frolunda, his team for six seasons before coming to North America. 
</P>
<P>
 Chances of that were slim, according to Duck General Manager Jack Ferreira, 
who last week said: 
</P>
<P>
 "He can do what he wants, but I'm not going to assign him there. I don't think 
there is any way to stop him. But certainly he's violating his contract. If he 
were to get hurt, we wouldn't be responsible." 
</P>
<P>
 Carnback had 23 points (12 goals, 11 assists) for the Ducks last season and 
played for Sweden in the World Championships last spring. 
</P>
<P>
 "The kid is in his option year," Abbott said. "He's not in a solid position. 
The risk is obviously greater long-term if he doesn't play. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think at this point there's no reason not to (play in Sweden). Call me a 
pessimist, but I believe we're not going to have an NHL season in any 
recognizable form." ROBYN NORWOOD 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
